{{ja-kanjitab|つき|yomi=k}}

{{IPAfont|⟨tuki<sub>2</sub>⟩}} → *{{IPAchar|/tukʷɨ/}} → *{{IPAchar|/t͡sukʷi/}} → {{IPAchar|/t͡suki/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|月|tr=tuki<sub>2</sub>}} (cf. phonetic Man'yōgana forms {{ltc-l|都奇|id=1,2}} and {{ltc-l|追奇|id=1,2}}), from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|*tukuy}}. Cognate with {{cog|jpx-ryu-pro|*tuki}}, whence {{cog|ams|てぃき|tr=tɨkˀi}}, {{cog|xug|しちー|tr=ɕitɕiː}}, {{cog|ryu|ちち|tr=tɕitɕi}}, {{cog|mvi|つきぃ|tr=tsɿkɿ}}, {{cog|rys|つぃくぃ|tr=tsɨkˢɨ}} and {{cog|yoi|ってぃー|tr=tˀiː}}.<ref name="Perard 2012">{{cite-web|first=Thomas|last=Pellard|title=日琉祖語の分岐年代|work=琉球諸語と古代日本語に関する比較言語学的研究」ワークショップ|year=2012|url=http://kikigengo.jp/nishihara/lib/exe/fetch.php?media=library:references:rkoj-pellard.pdf|page=6}}</ref>

Likely a shift from ''tsuku'' (see below), derived through a fusion with ancient Japanese emphatic nominal particle {{ja-r|い}}.  Compare the development of {{m|ja|神|tr=kami||[[Shinto]] [[deity]]}} from older combining form ''kamu''.

